Afghanistan: Voter registration in danger.
Afghanistan's Election Commission has announced that it is delaying voter registration in some areas of the south due to concerns over security.
In southern Afghanistan, voter registration had to be started this week for the upcoming presidential election.
The commission has stated that voters in a few areas of the province Hilmand will not be able to get registered unless the security situation improves.
In those parts of the south, conflict has increased from last year, where rebel Taliban members have increased attacks on Afghan and international forces.
Meanwhile, Afghan and international forces have said that overnight from Wednesday into Thursday, they have killed at least 28 militants in battles across Afghanistan.
NATO claimed that its military forces killed 22 enemy soldiers in land and air strikes in the Western province of Khost, near the Pakistani border.
Previously, the Afghan Defense Ministry had claimed that the Afghan army had killed eight rebels and injured two within the province.
It is not clear whether the Afghani officeholders are referring to the same incident.
Two missile attacks in Waziristan, at least 18 killed.
Pakistan Intelligence officials have said that in two doubtful American missile attacks in North Waziristan, at least 18 people were killed.
According to these officials, unmanned planes fired three missiles on a house in Mir province of north Waziristan, killing ten.
According to local officials, five of the dead were non-national soldiers.
This region is considered the center of Taliban and Al-Qaidah activity.
A few hours after this incident, a missile attack was occurred on south Waziristan as well, killing at least 8 more.
Despite the objections of the Pakistani government, there have been about 30 missile attacks since mid-last year.
The present attacks were the first since President Barack Obama took office.
The Bush government had been avoiding acknowledging the attacks.
On Friday, suspected American spy planes dropped three missiles in the tribal region of North Waziristan. Five deaths have been reported.
The dead could not be identified.
According to initial reports the missile attacks were on a house in the locality of Mir Ali.
It should be noted that these are the first missile attacks on the tribal regions of Pakistan since Barack Obama became president.
Sarhad state officials reject demand to restrict girls' education.
In Sarhad state, officials have rejected the Taliban's warning to restrict girls education, saying that this announcement is against both law and Islam.
On Sunday, the education minister of Sarhad state, Sardar Husain Babar, added that the government will never allow such efforts to succeed.
He said that the extremists are attempting to deprive our region's children of education.
In his words: ""These people try to secretly blow up schools and frighten the boys and girls""
Talking about the environment of fear and insecurity, he said that the local government knows well and wants it to be known that no force can stop the spread of education in the land of the Pukhtons.
One day ago, the Taliban soldiers, led by Moulana Fazlullah, had demanded that girls be banned from studying in the Swat's educational institutions beginning on the 15th of January.
Despite the military activity going on in Swat during the last one and a half years, about 150 educational institutions were destroyed by the militants by the use of explosives and arson.
Due to the destruction of these educational institutions, thousands of girls and boys were deprived of an education.
Strict security arrangements in India on Republic Day.
The 60th Republic Day is being celebrated in India on Monday. On this occasion, strict security measures are being taken and thousands of soldiers were posted throughout the country.
On the occasion of Republic Day, during the army parade in New Delhi, weapons, planes and other military equipment is displayed.
Officials are saying that the security arrangements include anti aircraft missiles and sharpshooters and that police will be deployed to watch the roads of the parade. American President Barack Obama congratulated India on the occasion.
And he also wished Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, who had undergone a heart operation on Saturday, a speedy recovery.
Indian police claim to have killed two suspected Pakistani fighters near New Delhi after an encounter yesterday.
According to local government the police recovered AK47 rifles, grenades, and papers from both persons which indicated that they were probably from Pakistan.
Police are also investigating into whether these two people belonged to the banned organization 'Lashkar-e-Taiba' which was involved in last November's Mumbai attacks.
Tea may help prevent breast cancer
According to new research, drinking three cups of tea every day
the risk for breast cancer is reduced by more than one third  in women under 50 years old.
Research conducted by the MOFT center in Florida, USA, has found that women under 50 years age that have breast cancer genes
The risk of breast cancer is reduced by 37 percent in women who drink three cups of tea per day.
The research shows that women over 50 years of age do not see any benefit from drinking three or more cups of tea a day.
The researchers think that for women under 50, the tea contains elements that are effective against the genes that cause breast cancer.
Research was done on 5000 women who had Breast Cancer treatment at Moffitt Cancer Center in Tampa,Florida.
Their ages were between 20 and 74 years.
Specialists compared their medical records and lifestyles to those women who were free of breast cancer.
Specialists also found that tea had the most effect on one specific kind of breast cancer, Lobes.  It reduced the risk by 66%.
One on every ten breast cancer patients has this kind of cancer.
This type of breast cancer is dangerous because it is deep inside and usually only diagnosed when it has become widespread.
Specialists found that having at least three cups of tea every day can readily reduce the chances of breast cancer in women of younger ages.
They found that incorporating tea as a regular drink in your daily routine helps create immunity against the cancer.
Almost 40,000 women are diagnosed with breast cancer in Britain.
According to Gates, the war in Afghanistan is the greatest military challenge facing America
American Defense Minister Robert Gates has said that the war in Afghanistan is the biggest military challenge faced by America.
Gates will give a briefing today to the Senate and House over the strategies of the Obama office on the Afghanistan and Iraq wars.
Gates told the Senate Armed Services committee that fighting is not the only solution to the Afghanistan issue. But he added that in order to secure several areas, sufficient numbers of troops are not deployed, and the Taliban take advantage of that to continue their operations.
Why Reduce Exercise With Age?
New Research
Exercise at any age is good for your health.
It energizes your heart, reduces cholesterol levels, helps in keeping weight low, helps to prevent diabetes and slows down the process of Alzheimer's or dementia.
Unfortunately the ability to exercise decreases for many people as they age.
Experts say that exercise keeps our body and brain active however age can affect it.
According to the American Medical Association, several health related problems can arise from not doing exercise.
Dr. Pattricia P. Leka of the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota says that increase in age is a big reason for being handicapped from exercise and other physical activity.
Dr. Patricia teaches medicine at Mayo clinic.
She headed a research study regarding heart disease and man's ability to do exercise in older age.
A team of doctors used high frequency sound waves to observe the performance of heart
in which it's activity of pumping blood and its contraction and relaxation was studied.
Researcher focused their attention on the right side of the heart, which is the main part of pumping blood.
They came to know ,that with increase in age, problems increase in the relaxation action of heart.
Dr. Patricia says with increase in age, problems occur in the activity of relaxation of heart and this effects the ability to exercise.
Dr. Garvin Ken was also part of this research.
He says that they were surprised to see that it has an effect  and it confirmed that bad exercising ability is very much related to the heart relaxing activity.
Sometimes blood pressure can cause disorders in heart functions and heart disease.
If the doctor and the patient work in tandem in this regard, the patient can take advantage of the benefits of exercise regardless of age.
A detailed report on this matter is published in a magazine from the American Medical Association.
No Chances of an Immediate War with Pakistan: Indian Army Chief
Indian Army Chief General Deepak Kapoor has said that there are no chances of an immediate war with Pakistan. "However/ we are always ready to defend our country and sacrifice our lives for it," he said.
He has stated that even with commitments from other nations and international pressure on Pakistan as a result of Mumbai attacks, the infrastructure of terrorism is not only existent but also proactive in Pakistan.
He said this while talking to correspondents in Srinagar.
The Indian Army Chief was on a one day tour to the valley of Kashmir in order to analyze the overall security situation in New Delhi-administered Kashmir and preparation of armed forces on the borders.
He was asked his thoughts on media reports that Pakistan has rejected the evidence provided from India regarding the Mumbai attacks.
General Kapoor said that the decisions of peace or war matters are made by the political leadership.
Talking about terrorism in the land of Pakistan, he allegedly said that India will fight against the forces that are trying to destroy peace and weaken India.
He said that there are around 700 to 800 fighters present in Indian Kashmir, of whom almost 50% are foreigners.
General Deepak Kapoor said that the governmental efforts of encroachment between Pakistan and Kashmir would be increased only when the weather improved, although India has increased security on the boarders.
They have refused the possibility of reducing the number of army soldiers in Indian Kashmir by stating that one can not compromise over the country's security.
